<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-451-439  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 451 439.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Sept 1990 v7 n9 p48(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The silver lining in Windows Version 3.0. (As I see it) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Craze, Camille.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Version 3.0 of Microsoft Windows brings nothing new in the way offeatures, yet the package has met with overwhelming enthusiasm,and Microsoft's Bill Gates predicts it will be outselling DOSwithin a year.andP;  Understanding the appeal of Windows 3.0 requireslooking at the overall product combination, not merely thefeatures: it is a DOS environment capable of serving as an OS/2Presentation Manager alternative for some user and it isefficient.andP;  The 640Kbyte memory barrier is gone.andP;  Where earlierversions of Windows tolerated networks 3.0 opens up newpossibilities for better networks.andP;  The graphical user interface(GUI) is not only more user friendly, it more closely resemblesPresentation Manager, moving users closer to OS/2 and allowing 3.0to serve as either a permanent solution for the low end of themarket or as a 'bridge' to OS/2.andP;  While there are somecompatibility problems with applications not written specificallyfor version 3.0 this appears to be a transient problem, andWindows 3.0 looks sure to have a long life.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Software PackagesCritiqueEnhancementsGraphical User InterfaceAnalysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>